TY  - JOUR
T1  - What Can Survey Forecasts Tell Us about Information Rigidities?
AU  - Coibion, Olivier
AU  - Gorodnichenko, Yuriy
Y1  - 2012/02/01
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/665662
DO  - 10.1086/665662
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 116
EP  - 159
VL  - 120
IS  - 1
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - A lot. We derive common and conflicting predictions from models in which agents face information constraints and then assess their validity using surveys of consumers, firms, central bankers, and professional forecasters. We document that mean forecasts fail to completely adjust on impact to shocks, leading to statistically and economically significant deviations from the null of full information. The dynamics of forecast errors after shocks are consistent with the predictions of models with information rigidities. The conditional responses of forecast errors and disagreement among agents can also be used to differentiate between some of the most prominent models of information rigidities.
AB  - A lot. We derive common and conflicting predictions from models in which agents face information constraints and then assess their validity using surveys of consumers, firms, central bankers, and professional forecasters. We document that mean forecasts fail to completely adjust on impact to shocks, leading to statistically and economically significant deviations from the null of full information. The dynamics of forecast errors after shocks are consistent with the predictions of models with information rigidities. The conditional responses of forecast errors and disagreement among agents can also be used to differentiate between some of the most prominent models of information rigidities.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/665662
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/665662
Y2  - 2024/03/20
